s for a 500 kW\nsynchronverter.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 16 Oct 2016 13:30:49 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-18"}
{"id":"1610.04859","submitter":"Thomas D. Galley","authors":"Thomas D. Galley and Lluis Masanes","title":"Classification of all alternatives to the Born rule in terms of\n  informational properties","comments":"9 pages main body, 16 pages appendices and 4 figures","journal-ref":"Quantum 1, 15 (2017)","doi":"10.22331/q-2017-07-14-15","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The standard postulates of quantum theory can be divided into two groups: the\nfirst one characterizes the structure and dynamics of pure states, while the\nsecond one specifies the structure of measurements and the corresponding\nprobabilities. In this work we keep the first group of postulates and\ncharacterize all alternatives to the second group that give rise to\nfinite-dimensional sets of mixed states. We prove a correspondence between all\nthese alternatives and a class of representations of the unitary group. Some\nfeatures of these probabilistic theories are identical to quantum theory, but\nthere are important differences in others. For example, some theories have\nthree perfectly distinguishable states in a two-dimensional Hilbert space.\nOthers have exotic properties such as lack of \"bit symmetry\", the violation of\n\"no simultaneous encoding\" (a property similar to information causality) and\nthe existence of maximal measurements without phase groups. We also analyze\nwhich of these properties single out the Born rule.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 16 Oct 2016 13:38:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 1 Dec 2016 16:03:01 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 13 Jun 2017 14:13:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-18"}
